# Testing Standards

<version>2.0.0</version>

## Context
- Apply when writing or modifying Cypress test files
- Focus on maintaining code quality through comprehensive testing
- Prioritize clear, maintainable, and meaningful tests
- Ensure test coverage meets minimum requirements
- All tests should be run using pnpm commands from the project root

## Requirements

### Test Execution
- Run tests using pnpm commands from the project root directory:
  - `pnpm cypress:run` - Run all E2E tests
  - `pnpm cypress:open` - Open Cypress Test Runner for interactive testing
  - `pnpm cypress:component:run` - Run all component tests
  - `pnpm cypress:component:open` - Open Cypress Component Test Runner
- Never prepend commands with directory changes (e.g., use `pnpm cypress:run` not `cd path/to/project && pnpm cypress:run`)
- Regularly run tests during development to catch issues early

### Coverage Requirements
- Maintain a minimum of 80% code coverage across the codebase
- Coverage requirements apply to:
  - 80% statement coverage
  - 80% branch coverage
  - 80% function coverage
  - 80% line coverage
- Cypress does not provide built-in code coverage, so coverage is assessed through:
  - Component tests covering component logic
  - E2E tests covering critical user flows
  - Manual review of test coverage for new features
- Address any coverage gaps in pull requests

### Test Organization
- Component tests should be in `cypress/component/` directory
- E2E tests should be in `cypress/e2e/` directory
- Page Objects should be in `cypress/pages/` directory
- Custom commands should be in `cypress/support/commands.ts`
- Test files should mirror the structure of the source code

### Test Naming Conventions
- Component tests: `ComponentName.cy.tsx` or `ComponentName.cy.jsx`
- E2E tests: `feature-name.cy.ts` or `feature-name.cy.js`
- Page Objects: `PageName.ts`
- Use descriptive names that indicate what is being tested

### Test Structure
- Use `describe()` blocks to group related tests
- Use `it()` blocks for individual test cases
- Use `beforeEach()` and `afterEach()` for setup and teardown
- Keep tests focused and independent
- Use Page Object Model for E2E tests to improve maintainability

### Best Practices
- Test user behavior, not implementation details
- Use `data-testid` attributes for stable element selection
- Use role-based or accessibility-based selectors when possible
- Avoid hard-coded waits; use Cypress automatic waiting
- Use custom commands for reusable test actions
- Keep tests simple and readable
- Test both happy paths and error cases
- Clean up test data after each test

### Component Testing
- Use `mount()` from `cypress/react18` for React components
- Test component rendering, interactions, and state changes
- Test different prop combinations and states
- Test error states and edge cases
- Use appropriate providers (ThemeProvider, etc.) when needed

### E2E Testing
- Test complete user flows from start to finish
- Use Page Object Model for maintainable test code
- Test authentication and authorization flows
- Test form submissions and validations
- Test navigation between pages
- Use `cy.session()` for caching login sessions

### Custom Commands
- Create custom commands for reusable test actions
- Define custom commands in `cypress/support/commands.ts`
- Add TypeScript types for custom commands
- Use descriptive names for custom commands
- Document custom commands with JSDoc comments

### Page Object Model
- Create Page Object classes for each page
- Encapsulate page elements and actions
- Use descriptive method names
- Keep Page Objects focused on page-specific logic
- Reuse Page Objects across multiple tests

